ğŸ“¦ Understanding Pods in Kubernetes:-
ğŸ”¹ Pod is the smallest deployable unit in a Kubernetes cluster
ğŸ“Œ Think of it as a wrapper for one or more tightly coupled containers
ğŸ› ï¸ Containers inside a pod share the same IP, storage, and namespace
ğŸ”„ They can communicate with each other easily and share volumes
ğŸ¯ Kubernetes interacts with Pods, not individual containers

ğŸ› ï¸ How to Create Pods
ğŸ”¸ Imperative Approach (CLI):
     âœkubectl run nginx-pod --image=nginx
ğŸ” View Your Pod:
     âœkubectl get pods
ğŸ”¸ Declarative Approach (YAML):
      1. Create a file:
     âœvim nginx-pod.yaml
2. Define your pod structure with:
   âœ…apiVersion
   âœ…kind: Pod
   âœ…metadata: (name, labels)
   âœ…spec: (image, ports, etc.)
3.  Apply the YAML:
  âœkubectl apply -f nginx-pod.yaml
ğŸ” Pod Lifecycle Insight
âš ï¸ If a pod fails (due to memory, network issues, etc.), it will not restart by default.
 âœ… Use ReplicaSets or Deployments to automatically manage pod availability and ensure fault tolerance.

